0.body: Radium is a game engine built with Java and the LWJGL tools. The documentation will go over how to use the editor and all the tools, along with the scripting system. Radium is currently a fairly small project, only being worked on by one person. I do want the engine to grow to have most of the features modern day game engines should have, and all the tools necessary for creating a game. The whole engine is free and open source, so all features can stay free forever, never any payments. This also allows games to be distributed for free, without payment to Radium, making it great for all games.
0.title: Welcome To Radium!

1.body: There is no official installer or executable currently for Radium, making the only way to install it is to download the source code and compile it yourself. As of now, Radium is only available for Windows.
1.title: Installing Radium

10.body: The menu bar is the top bar of the editor. It contains features with project management, preferences, and hidden windows. The file tab is useful for project management. You can open scenes, save scenes, and even open your project in VSCode. The edit tab is used for your preferences. Change how your editor looks with themes. The Run tab is used for playing or stopping your scene. The Window tab is used for hidden windows. Hidden windows are windows that can be opened and closed.

14.body: You can create new objects by right clicking in the window. It will open a popup. These options include creating an empty object, with no components at all. There will also be a dropdown menu that allows you to create multiple types of objects including meshes, lights, and cameras. Right cliking on a game object will also open a different popup menu. This menu contains options to delete the object and create a prefab. Prefabs are a file version of a game object. You can drag a prefab into your scene and a replica of the object will be made. Demo

24.body: There are a few small things that should be kept in mind when writing python with Radium. You should not use the import keyword for any Radium related imports. This is because it is not supported by Radium, and everything is already automatically imported. You cannot import other files you have written into your program. There might be a fix soon, but for now, everything must be contained inside one file. Do not edit any variables directly in a class. Instead use the dedicated getter and setter methods. And if there is no getter or setter method for the field, it should not be changed at all.
24.title: Radium Scripting Notes

294.body: Find examples for systems such as scripting, shaders, and other development related tasks. This is a great place to learn how to use these systems as well.
294.title: Notes

295.body: You will learn how to use the python scripting system to make a simple script. This script will be able to control the movement of a game object. It will use keyboard input and will move the game object in the direction of the arrow keys. You can see the final result down at the bottom of the page.
295.breadcrumbs: Examples » First Script » Your First Script
295.title: Your First Script

296.body: Make sure you have a project created. If you don't know how to do this, refer to the creating a project section of the Installing Radium guide. Also after updating your script, make sure to go to the inspector window and click update scripts button on the python scripting component.
296.title: Notes

297.body: Create an empty game object by using the Scene Hierarchy and select it. This will bring up all of the components and properties inside of the Inspector window. At the bottom of all the components you will find the add component button. Then find under scripting, the python scripting component. We then need to create our script. Go to your project and create a new file. You can name it anything, just make sure it has the extension .py. Next under your python scripting component, you will find the add script button. This button will open a file explorer, choose your newly created file.
297.breadcrumbs: Examples » First Script » Creating the Script
297.title: Creating the Script

298.body: Open up your script in some sort of editor. You can use a text editor such as VSCode or even notepad. The first things we need to define are the start and update methods. In your script write: def start(): pass def update(): pass The start method is called once when the game starts. The update method is called every frame.
298.breadcrumbs: Examples » First Script » Setting Up the Script
298.title: Setting Up the Script

299.body: We now need to get the keyboard input. We can do this by calling Input.isKeyDown() This method takes in a string as a parameter. This will return a bool, true if the key is down, false if it is not. We can show this by logging it to the console. Write in your update method: log(Input.isKeyDown("w")) This will print out true if the w key is down, false if it is not.
299.breadcrumbs: Examples » First Script » Getting Keyboard Input
299.title: Getting Keyboard Input

3.body: To download the source from github, first select the branch you want to download from the dropdown menu. Then, click the "Clone or download" button as in the example below. Github Clone Demo
3.title: Downloading from Github

30.body: transform ( Transform ) components ( Component []) name (string) id (string) parent ( GameObject ) destroyed (bool)
30.title: Properties

300.body: We can alter the position of the game object by using the keyboard data. To add to the position of the game object, refer to the GameObject.translate() method. It takes in a Vector3 as a parameter. The vector3 is the amount of units to move the game object. We can use the keyboard to move the game object up, down, left, or right. Delete the last line logging whether a key is down and write this in your update method: if Input.isKeyDown("w"): gameObject.translate(Vector3(0, 1, 0)) While this will work, it will not work as intented. The game object will fly off very fast. There is an easy work around to this.
300.breadcrumbs: Examples » First Script » Using Keyboard Input
300.title: Using Keyboard Input

301.body: If we tell our script to change the position one unit every frame, the position will change a lot more in one second than one unit. If our game is running 60fps, this means it is moving 60 units in a second. A way we can fix this is by multiplying our speed by deltaTime. Delta time is the time between frames. If we run 60fps, delta time will be equal to 1/60 or 0.016. Since our game is running at 60fps, multiplying it by 1/60 will make our object move 1 unit every second instead of every frame. Change your code to: if Input.isKeyDown("w"): gameObject.translate(Vector3(0, Time.deltaTime(), 0)) Now our object will move up 1 unit every second.
301.title: Delta Time

302.body: We can change the speed of our object by multiplying Time.deltaTime() with a number. If I multiply it by 3, my object will move 3 units every second. Change your update function to: if Input.isKeyDown("w"): gameObject.translate(Vector3(0, Time.deltaTime() * 3, 0))
302.breadcrumbs: Examples » First Script » Changing the Speed
302.title: Changing the Speed

303.breadcrumbs: Examples » First Script » Adding Other Inputs
303.title: Adding Other Inputs

304.body: Your final script should look something like this: def start(): pass def update(): if Input.isKeyDown("w"): gameObject.translate(Vector3(0, Time.deltaTime() * 3, 0)) if Input.isKeyDown("a"): gameObject.translate(Vector3(Time.deltaTime() * 3, 0, 0)) if Input.isKeyDown("s"): gameObject.translate(Vector3(0, -Time.deltaTime() * 3, 0)) if Input.isKeyDown("d"): gameObject.translate(Vector3(-Time.deltaTime() * 3, 0, 0))
304.title: Final Script

5.body: There are really no good ways to currently run the engine. One way to run the engine is to open it in an IDE or editor such as IntelliJ IDEA or Eclipse. The second way is to build the project using gradle. Compiling the project with standard Java will fail because there are many dependencies handled by gradle.
5.title: Running Radium

After installing the CLI, make sure it is in your path. This article does a good job explaining how to do this. When this is finally setup, run the following command in the directory you want to the project to be in: radium create project-name This will create a project in the current directory with the name "project-name".
